In an emergency call, professor confesses to shooting his girlfriend
In an emergency call, Professor Shannon Lamb told police in a somewhat shaky voice that he had shot his girlfriend and that officers needed to come to his house.
Lamb was keen to stress that his "sweet dog" was alive, however, and probably upset, and he said the dead woman's family contacts could be found on her mobile phone.
Inside the house, officers found the body of Amy Prentiss and a handwritten note scrawled on a white pad, "I'm so sorry, I wish I could take it back, I loved Amy and she is the only woman who ever loved me." This is what the letter said, according to authorities, and it was signed by Lamb.
There was no indication that Lamb, who taught two online courses for Delta State University in Cleveland, Mississippi, had already travelled 300 miles to the school campus where police say he shot and killed a popular history professor, Ethan Schmidt, at the door to his office.
Delta State University Police Chief Lynn Buford said university staff heard the shooting at 10:18am.
He said Lamb made the fatal 911 call sometime after that.
By the end of the day, there was one more death: Lamb took his own life as police closed in on him.
A day after the university shooting that forced students and faculty to hide behind locked doors, authorities are still trying to get a picture of what motivated Lamb.
Details released by investigators at both ends of the state, as well as what students and staff who knew him testified to, helped paint a picture of a talented but potentially difficult teacher.
Students said they looked forward to his classes.
Police in Gautier, where Prentiss died, said he had no history of violence or criminal history.
Schmidt himself had mentioned Lamb in a book he wrote about the "wonderful people" with whom he shared his academic life.
Both taught in the Social Sciences and History Department, which has a faculty of 17, and many students took courses from both.
At the same time, there were some tendencies towards problematic behaviour.
One student, Brandon Beavers, who praised Lamb, said he also seemed a little agitated and nervous, "like there was something wrong with him."
Another student, Mikel Sykes, said Lamb told him he was dealing with stress at the end of the 2014-15 academic year.
Lamb had previously asked Delta State University for a leave of absence for health reasons, saying he had some health problem.
He taught only two online courses that year.
Recent changes in the university's employment policy meant that the doctorate Lamb had worked so hard for would not guarantee him an automatic path to tenure as an assistant professor.
University President William LaForge said he knew of no conflict between Lamb and Schmidt, but "of course there was something in Mr Lamb's mind."
These are questions Lamb can no longer answer.
After fleeing the campus, police later found Lamb's trail as he was driving back into Mississippi from Arkansas.
Before he could be apprehended, Lamb killed himselfwith a .38 calibre pistol in the backyard of a home about a mile south of his parents' home on the outskirts of Greenville, Mississippi, said Washington County Coroner Methel Johnson.
His car was still running in the driveway.
It was not immediately clear why Lamb went to that house, but Johnson said she believed he knew the people who lived there.
Lamb grew up in the area.
Lamb began working at the university, which has 3,500 students in a town of about 12,000, in 2009, teaching geography and education.
He earned his doctorate in education in the spring.
One of Lamb's longtime friends described him as intelligent, charismatic and funny.
Carla Hairston said she was 15 and Lamb was 20 when they met through mutual friends.
She and her friends were in high school, and he was the cool older guy who spent a few years trying to teach her how to play the guitar.
He was the ladies' man back then.
All the girls melted when he was around," said Hairston, now 40 and living in the Jackson suburb of Brandon.
Lamb and Prentiss apparently dated for some time.
In the 911 call, Lamb said "I killed my wife," but there was no record of a marriage.
They had a dog named Lightning who lived with them in the brick house that abuts a bayou in Gautier.
Police said the dog was fine.
Prentiss' ex-husband, Shawn O'Steen, said they had divorced 15 years ago but remained friends and had a daughter who was now 19.
"She was absolutely devastated," O'Steen said of his daughter.
She and her mother were absolutely best friends.
O'Steen said he never met Lamb, but heard through his daughter Abigail that Lamb was interested in music and played blues.
Lamb met Prentiss when he and Abigail both performed at a summer fair three years ago.
They later played the odd gig together.
O'Steen said his daughter writes and sings her own music.
Prentiss was a nurse who worked for various businesses online.
Mike Shaffer, a bartender and sometimes entertainment coordinator at The Julep Room, a dimly lit bar near Gautier, said he last saw Lamb and Prentiss Night on Sept. 5 after Lamb finished playing his guitar and harmonica to a sparse audience.
There was no sign that anything was wrong.
"Just a happy couple," he said.
We were cleaning up and joking with each other.
I mean, they both had a good sense of banter.
Schmidt, the dead professor, ran the freshman seminar programme and specialised in Native American and colonial history, said Don Allan Mitchell, an English professor at the school.
He was married with three young children.
He studied at Emporia State University in Kansas and was president of his fraternity and sorority committee.
On the Delta State campus in Cleveland, about 900 people, including faculty, staff, students and members of the community attended a candlelight memorial service Tuesday evening.
Schmidt's wife Liz and brother Jeff Schmidt also attended the vigil, while the university choir sang "Bright Morning Star" and "Amazing Grace."
Classes will resume on Wednesday.
"We are trying to get our students to return," LaForge said.
The crisis is over.
This is a day of healing.
Amy and Rogelio Solis reported from Cleveland, Mississippi.
Associated Press writers Emily Wagster Pettus in Greenville, Mississippi, and Rebecca Santana in New Orleans contributed to this report.
This story has been corrected to reflect that police now say Lamb made the 911 call after he shot Schmidt, and that while Lamb referred to Prentiss as his wife in his 911 call, there is no indication the two ever married.
Toys R Us plans to hire fewer workers for Christmas season
Toys R Us says it will not hire as many Christmas seasonal employees as it did last year, but the toy and baby products retailer says it will give employees and seasonal workers currently employed by it a chance to work more hours.
The company said it plans to hire 40,000 people at shops and distribution centres across the country. It still hired 45,000 workers during the 2014 Christmas season.
Most of the jobs will be part-time.
The company said it will start interviewing people this month and the headcount will increase from October to December.
While the holidays themselves are still months away, the Christmas shopping season is approaching and companies are preparing to hire temporary workers to staff shops to sell, ship and deliver products.
Michael J. Fox jokes about his "date" with Princess Diana
The premiere of "Back to the Future" was a big moment professionally for Michael J. Fox.
It was also remarkable for personal reasons.
"We were sitting in the theatre waiting for the royals, and I realise the seat next to me is empty, and it's starting to hit me that Princess Diana is going to be sitting next to me," he said in a trailer for an upcoming documentary, "Back in Time."
The film begins and it occurs to me that I am a simulated yawn and an arm's length away from being on a date with the Princess of Wales.
"Back in Time", a documentary about "Back to the Future", presents interviews with Fox, Lea Thompson and Christopher Lloyd, as well as director Robert Zemeckis and producer Steven Spielberg.
"Back for the Future" premiered 30 years ago.
"It's really, to me," Spielberg said, "indisputably the greatest time travel movie ever made."
"Back in Time" will be available on VOD, DVD and in selected cinemas in October.
UN chief says there is no military solution in Syria
Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon says his response to Russia's increased military support for Syria is that "there is no military solution" to the nearly five-year conflict, and more weapons will only exacerbate violence and misery for millions of people.
The UN chief is again calling on all parties, including the divided UN Security Council, to unite and support inclusive negotiations to find a political solution.
Ban told a news conference on Wednesday that he plans to meet the foreign ministers of the Council's five permanent member nations - the US, Russia, China, the UK and France - on the sidelines of the General Assembly ministerial session later this month to discuss the situation in Syria.
He regretted that divisions within the Council and within the Syrian people and regional powers "make this situation intractable."
Ban called on the five permanent members to show the same solidarity and unity in addressing the crisis in Syria that they have shown in reaching a nuclear deal with Iran.
8 Poll numbers that show Donald Trump is to be taken seriously.
Some have tried to brand him a flop.
Others have dismissed him as a joke.
And some are waiting for a meltdown.
But no matter how some Republicans try to drag Donald Trump down from the top ranks in polls, it hasn't worked (yet).
Ten of the last eleven national polls showed Donald Trump leading by double digits, and some are beginning to seriously wonder what it means for the real estate mogul's chances of winning the nomination.
Of course, it is still early in the election cycle.
No one is suggesting that Trump is likely to win the Republican nomination.
Pundits point out that at this time in 2011 Rick Perry's lead was ceded to the rising Herman Cain, neither of whom won a single state in the nomination process.
And there are many reasons why he would struggle in a general election.
But outsider groups like Jeb Bush's Super PAC and the conservative business group Club for Growth now recognise Trump's staying power and are starting to flow their dollars to bring him down.
Here are some recent poll numbers that suggest the real estate mogul is not just a passing phase:
Trump's approval ratings have turned 180 degrees.
Shortly before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a Monmouth University poll showed that only two in ten Republicans viewed the real estate mogul favourably.
By mid-July, it was 40 per cent.
By early August, it was 52 per cent.
Now six in 10 Republicans have a positive view of Donald Trump.
About three in 10 say they have a negative view.
And those numbers hold up in early states.
A Quinnipiac poll in Iowa last week found that 60 percent of Republicans have a good opinion of Trump.
Two-thirds of GOP voters GOP would be happy with Trump as their nominee.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67 percent of Republicans said they would be either "thrilled" or "satisfied" if Trump were nominated.
Only two in 10 say they would be "upset" if he were the nominee.
Only Ben Carson manages about the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43 percent say they would be "thrilled" vs. 40 percent who say the same about Trump).
Next in terms of enthusiasm?
Marco Rubio with just 21 percent.
On the other hand, 47 percent of Republican voters say they would be "dissatisfied" or "upset" if Jeb Bush, the establishment favourite, became the nominee.
A majority of Republicans do not see Trump's temperament as a problem.
While Donald Trump is widely criticised for his bombastic and offensive statements, 52 percent of Irish voters leaning Republican believe the real estate mogul has the right temperament for a president, ABC News/Washington Post reported on Monday.
The same figure holds true in the nation's first primary state, Iowa, where the same 52 percent of Republicans think he has the personality for a commander-in-chief, according to Quinnipiac last week.
Still, 44 percent think he doesn't have the personality to effectively carry out his office, and nearly six in 10 independents say his temperament doesn't fit in the White House, according to ABC/Post.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When they put on their scholar hats, Republican voters think Trump is real.
When asked who is most likely to win the GOP nomination, four in ten say Trump is the best bet, according to a CNN/ORC poll from last week.
That's a change from when four in ten put their money on Jeb Bush in late July.
Full disclosure: GOP voters haven't had the clearest crystal ball in the past.
At this point in the last cycle, four in ten Republicans thought Rick Perry would win the nomination versus just 28% for the eventual nominee, Mitt Romney.
Still, it turns out that a plurality of GOP voters see Trump's campaign as plausible.
Even if Republicans rallied around another candidate, Trump still beats almost everyone.
Some experts point out that the fractured field is likely contributing to Trump's lead, while anti-Trump support is diffused among more than a dozen other candidates.
But a Monmouth University poll in early September shows that in a hypothetical head-to-head race between Trump and most other Republican candidates, Trump reaps the majority support.
He is 13 points ahead of Carly Fiorina, 14 points ahead of Marco Rubio, 15 points ahead of Walker, 19 points ahead of Jeb Bush and finally 33 points ahead of Rand Paul, John Kasich and Chris Christie.
It's a neck-and-neck race with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate to beat him?
Ben Carson would overtake the businessman by 19 points in a hypothetical head-to-head.
A slim majority of Donald Trump supporters say they have made up their minds.
A new CBS/NYT poll out Tuesday shows that just over half of voters who support Trump say they have their minds made up.
Of course, a lot can happen to change that, and no one can really say never change their mind.
46 percent said they leave the door open to switching to other candidates.
Still, Trump's strongest competition right now is the other outsider, neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but voters who say they've made up their minds are twice as likely to back Trump.
Six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
Ever since Donald Trump called immigrants from Mexico "rapists" in his campaign speech two months ago, immigration has been a linchpin in the public discourse on 2016.
Some are concerned that Trump's bombastic language will keep crucial Hispanics away from the Republican Party and damage the realignment effort.
But according to Monday's new ABC/Post poll, six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration issues.
So as long as immigration remains in the spotlight, it seems Donald Trump will too.
Frustration with the government is climbing to new highs.
Donald Trump and Ben Carson now account for about half of Republican voters' support, largely due to their outsider status.
Six in 10 Republicans in ABC/Post's new Monday poll say they'd rather have a political outsider than someone with government experience.
And they're angry at Washington, too.
A Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll in Iowa a fortnight ago shows three in four Iowa Republicans are frustrated with congressional Republicans, with 54 percent "dissatisfied" and 21 percent "angry as hell."
Jeremy Corbyn's debut at prime minister's question time
Since his election, Mr Corbyn's debut at Prime Minister's Question Time has been eagerly anticipated
New Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn is to make his debut at Prime Minister's Question Time, taking on David Cameron for the first time.
Mr Corbyn will rise to ask the first of his six pre-set questions shortly after noon, with his performance likely to be scrutinised by the media and Labour MPs up close.
He called for "less theatre and more facts" at this weekly event.
He also said he could skip some sessions to give to colleagues.
The meeting will be the first parliamentary test for Mr Corbyn's leadership as it comes after his appointment as a member of the shadow cabinet and his speech to the TUC annual conference on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to remain silent during the singing of the national anthem at a commemoration of the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain on Tuesday has provoked criticism from a number of Tory MPs and is the focus of several front-page stories in newspapers.
Mr Corbyn's decision not to sing national anthem has attracted attention
A spokesman for Mr Corbyn said he had "stood in respectful silence" and that he had recognised the "heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain".
But a member of Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told the BBC Two Newsnight programme he had advised the Labour leader to sing the national anthem "regardless" of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers have refused to serve in Mr Corbyn's top team, citing differences on the economy, defence and foreign policy, while less than a sixth of the Parliamentary Party originally backed him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says policy differences are also "stacking up" within Labour following Mr Corbyn's comments on the position on the European Union and the cap on gains.
Mr Corbyn told the TUC conference that Labour was tabling amendments to remove the whole idea of a cap altogether.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the shadow work and pensions minister, said the party was "very clear" that it was only opposed to government plans to cut the limit from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader to face David Cameron across the Dispatch Box in Parliament in the last decade since he became Tory leader.
The Labour leader, who has promised a different approach to politics, says he has "crowd-sourced" ideas for questions to Mr Cameron and has been given more than 30,000 suggestions.
The Islington North MP has said that Prime Minister's Question Time is too confrontational and that he will refrain from both "repartee" and barbed arguing, instead setting out to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people.
Mr Corbyn has said that Angela Eagle, the Shadow Business Secretary will stand in for him when he is not attending - for example when Mr Cameron is away abroad.
He has also floated the idea of other colleagues speaking up occasionally, and that he had approached John Bercow, the Speaker of the House of Commons, to discuss the issue.
When he became leader in 2005, Mr Cameron said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics often associated with Prime Minister's Question Time. But a few years later he conceded that he had failed at it.
Since it was first televised in 1990, Prime Minister's Question Hour has been seen as the most important barometer of a leader's judgement and leadership in the House of Commons and his standing among his parliamentary colleagues, although critics have argued that it has become a caricature and needs far-reaching reforms.
'Shot in Joburg': homeless youths trained as photographers
Johannesburg's city centre is a tough place to be if you're homeless.
But a group of former street kids have found a way to learn a skill and earn a living.
"I was shot in Joburg" is a non-profit studio that teaches homeless youth how to take photos of their surroundings and make a profit from it.
BBC News met one of the project's first graduates.
