Pound rises as UK wage growth accelerates
The pound jumped after data showed a surge in UK wage growth. In parallel, the FTSE 100 was boosted by bid target SABMiller.
Between May and July, UK earnings excluding bonuses grew by 2.9% compared to the same period last year.
This percentage was the fastest since 2009 and provided estimates of the timing of an interest rate rise.
The pound rose more than 1% against the dollar to $1.5505 and was up 0.84% against the euro to €1.3730.
The FTSE 100 index closed up 1.49% at 6,229.21.
SABMiller was the standout stock in the market, jumping 20% after receiving a takeover bid from rival AB InBev.
A deal would combine the world's two biggest brewers and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry shares were 0.9% higher after encouraging news from rival luxury goods group Richemont.
Richemont's latest sales figures beat all expectations and also showed that sales in China - a key market for Burberry - are reporting growth again.
Shares in Glencore rose 5 % after the mining giant said it raised $2.5 billion from a share sale as part of its debt reduction strategy.
Shares in packaging and paper group Mondi were the biggest losers on the index, falling 4.3 % after Goldman Sachs set its rating on the company to "sell".
JD Sports rose 3.1% after the sportswear company reported pre-tax profit of 46.6 million for the half-year.
JD Sports chief says higher wages threaten expansion.
JD Sports chief executive Peter Cowgill says a higher minimum wage for UK workers could mean "more spending power in the pockets of potential customers".
But it is unlikely that this spending power will offset higher labour costs at his company, he says.
The costs could hit JD Sports' expansion plans, he added, and that could mean fewer additional jobs.
Metcash launches ground-up campaign to fight Aldi incursion
Metcash is trying to protect IGA shops from an Aldi incursion in South Australia and Western Australia.
Grocery wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground-up campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
As Aldi prepares to open two distribution centres and the first 120 shops in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and social media marketing, as well as events such as Adelaide Show.
IGA retailers and suppliers are jumping on board, with brands such as Dunsborough-based ice cream maker Simmo handing out samples in IGA shops and shop owners selling discounted South Australian Football League tickets to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release more details of its defence strategy on 29 September when the food, alcohol and appliance wholesaler holds its annual investor strategy day.
The stakes are high as South Australia and Western Australia account for almost 30 per cent of Metcash's IGA shop business and generate higher profit margins than Metcash's IGA network in the eastern states.
Shoppers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - more than 30 per cent in South Australia and 24 per cent in Western Australia compared to around 14 per cent in the Eastern States.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe Aldi will snatch away about five per cent of the grocery market in these two states 12 months after opening its first stores, taking sales away from all existing players but mainly independent retailers.
According to a report released this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in sales a year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 shops in SA and 30 in WA next year, with sales of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in food and grocery and volume on Metcash's high fixed cost base could cost Metcash about $13 million in earnings before interest and tax, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the Eastern States, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent Roy Morgan survey found that IGA shoppers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley reckons Metcash's food and grocery sales will fall 3.8 per cent in 2016, 4.1 per cent in 2017 and 2.1 per cent in 2018, reducing its market share from 14 per cent in 2015 to 10.3 per cent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglass, founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash was likely within a decade. Metcash would disappear.
Metcash declined to respond publicly to Mr Douglass' comments.
But a Metcash board member is understood to have contacted Mr Douglass last week.
IGA's market share has fallen from 18 per cent to 14 per cent since 2010, and revenue from Metcash's food and grocery business, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen 43 per cent since 2012, reflecting operational deleveraging combined with pressure on sales and margins.
However, the wholesaler is fighting back, investing more than $150 million to align selling prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week and help IGA retailers improve their shops by growing fresh food faster and delivering a better range of private label food.
Metcash's chief executive Ian Morrice says the price adjustments and shop refurbishment programmes will gain momentum and hopes the wholesaler will return to profit growth in 2017 for the first time in four years.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is backed by Australian Tennis Federation president Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his conduct.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damage" in the recent storm surrounding his friend Nick Kyrgios and deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behaviour, according to Australian Tennis Federation president Steve Healy.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo repeatedly referred to as the "Special Ks", came into the spotlight because of Kyrgios' infamous clash with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying match in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the umpire, with Harrison exclaiming, "Wawrinka should have hit Kyrgios, and I should hit the kid."
While he was last seen smashing a tennis racket after a cramp thwarted a potential US Open win by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was staunchly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-finals against Great Britain.
"One thing I'm quite upset about is the fact that in my view Thanasi got a bit involved in the altercation," Healy said.
He broke a racket when he lost because of a cramp in the US Open, but he's not the first player to break a racket out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But, really, he did extremely well in the US Open, even in the rather provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of credit.
He's got a great team around him, he's got a great family around him, and I think he's been treated a little bit too harshly.
He's a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard and he fits in with the team and so on, he's never had a problem with the other players, he's respected in the dressing room, he trains hard, he's in good shape, he's a very stable and mature young lad and I think he deserves to be judged on his own merits.
Healy also backed the decision not to include Kyrgios in the all-important preliminary draw, which starts on Friday, and he describes the "joint decision" as the right thing to do for everyone, but assures the Canberra man will return to the team as a long-term permanent fixture."
"First of all, we want the team to be completely focused on the competition and not all the controversy around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And I think Nick has moved up the ladder very quickly, which people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He's rising in the eyes of the public and he's made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he's getting, but we're trying to support him, we're trying to make him understand the consequences of his actions. Some time out of the limelight where he can just think about it I think is appropriate and it's best for the team and it's best for him.
Europe's refugee crisis: Hungary declares state of emergency, closes border, detains refugees
Hungary declared a state of emergency and sealed off its southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, detaining anyone who tried to enter the country illegally. All with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos ensued at the border as hundreds of migrants piled into a no-man's land and Serbian officials reacted with outrage.
People fleeing violence were stuck for an unknown amount of time in a strip of land on the road between the countries' two checkpoints, erecting tents and settling there.
But frustrations mounted.
As a police helicopter hovered overhead, the migrants chanted "Open the border!" and shouted insults at the Hungarian riot police.
Some rejected food and water in protest.
Serbia's foreign minister said it was "unacceptable" that migrants were being sent back from Hungary while more and more were arriving from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not collateral damage.
There must be talks with Brussels and other countries in the coming days," Ivica Dacic said in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc failed to agree on a common immigration policy at a contentious meeting in Brussels.
However, ministers agreed to share responsibility for 40,000 people who sought refuge in Italy and Greece, which were caught off guard. They expressed hope that eventually - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached for EU states to take in another 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria on Tuesday called for a special European Union summit to discuss the continent's immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, was not pinning its hopes on any early action from Brussels or its neighbours.
The state of emergency declared in two southern regions on Tuesday gave authorities more powers to deal with the crisis, allowing them to close off roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto, meanwhile, said his country was also planning to build a barbed-wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the flow of migrants through the country - after finishing a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prison inmates were used in the race to build the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a significant bottleneck and entry point into the European Union for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
Prime Minister Viktor Orban, however, has insisted that most arrivals are economic refugees seeking a better life, not war refugees entitled to protection - a view strongly at odds with other EU states, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force in Hungary at midnight, make it a crime to cross the border or damage the 4-metre (13-foot) high fence the government has built along the southern border with Serbia. These laws also set higher prison sentences for convicted traffickers.
"Due to the situation created by mass migration, the Hungarian government declares a state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament has yet to procedurally approve the deployment of the military, which is expected next week, but Associated Press reporters have seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, country security adviser for Orban, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border, and 15 others had already entered deeper into the country.
They come across by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are quickly repairing the fence.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a train car carrying barbed wire to close the borders arrived.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, as Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process people's data and a crowd pushed to squeeze in.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands stayed outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main highway linking Serbia and Hungary, saying they would refuse food and water until they were allowed into Hungary.
Election-2016: Hillary Clinton's lead over Bernie Sanders halved in national poll
Former US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a double-digit lead in the Democratic race for the nomination nationally, but Senator Bernie Sanders is gaining ground on her.
Clinton now has the support of 47 per cent of Democratic voters in the primaries (58 per cent previously), while Sanders is in second place, with 27 per cent (up 17 per cent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether he will run for president, has support from 15 percent of Democratic primary voters.
More than five months before the primaries begin, most Democratic voters say it is too early to say their minds are made up about which candidate they will support.
But Clinton's supporters are more consistent in their choices than those of the other candidates.
Since the CBS News poll, Clinton has lost among a number of demographic groups, while Sanders has made some gains.
Clinton holds a large lead among women and moderates, but those leads have narrowed.
Her support among men has dropped significantly, and Sanders trails by only 5 points here.
