Here's what will happen if the Fed raises interest rates
A rate hike is coming, and the bull market will falter, bond yields will rise, and the economy will slide into recession.
We know that.
What we don't know is how long it will all take and how long it will last.
In particular, history offers little guidance for the economy on how it will play out.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first interest rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve's aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, though not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
That is why representatives of the US central bank have stressed so fiercely that investors should not focus on when it will start raising interest rates, but rather on the time it will take to normalise.
Indeed, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants may find that all the excitement about a rate hike may have been overdone.
"The Fed's first hike since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal of the end of the era of cheap money," Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
In contrast, we do not expect a gradual return of US interest rates to normal levels, but still at levels too low to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, that does not mean there will be no impact.
Here is a look, based on historical trends, at how some areas of the economy might react:
As the market saw last month, the anticipation of rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
Once the hike arrives, the impact is not as dramatic.
"There seems to be a tendency for asset returns to stall 12 to 24 months after the first hike, again perhaps reflecting the lag in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after Fed rate hikes.
More specifically, the market has been mostly in an uptrend over the past 35 years - about 14 per cent - on the way to the rate hike, fairly flat in the 250 days after (average gain of 2.6 per cent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return over the past six past cycles of 14.4 per cent according to a recent analysis Bob Doll, chief investment strategist at Nuveen Asset Management, published in Barron's.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on equities tends to occur later in the increase cycle and returns begin to decline as a result.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but rate hikes often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is faced with some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
Most notable in this case is that GDP will be near its lowest point when the Fed raises rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, in the 118 rate hikes since 1950, only twice has nominal GDP been below 4.5 per cent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 per cent, few expect this to last and expect only 1.5 per cent in the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising interest rates in such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky and raises the question "whether this time is different", Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been bracing for a Fed rate hike all year, and all eyes have been on this week's Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve a hike at that meeting, futures traders are only giving it a 25 per cent chance.
"In our study, all hike cycles from 1950 to the present have occurred in a super-cycle of increasing momentum in GDP, eclipsing pre-recession highs very quickly after the recovery began," the report said.
By contrast, this is clearly a slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the period observed.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income has also been volatile as the market anticipates a rate hike and the pattern is quite similar to the capital markets.
The main difference is that the effect is faster with bonds than with equities when they change their strategic course.
With bonds, yields seem to change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Strategists at Charles Schwab believe the rise in interest rates will cause yields between longer and shorter bonds to move closer together, leading to a flattening of the curve.
High-yield bonds often produce better returns in such a climate, although "we are still cautious about expecting higher returns," Kathy Jones, fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
What is interesting, Jones says, is that markets have already adjusted to Fed strategy expectations.
"In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy" she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have widened and volatility has increased - all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
By and large, companies that do the greater part of their business in the US will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinationals with large debts will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global marketplace and so does financing their debt.
"History shows that "quality" stocks tend to react overwhelmingly positively three months after an initial rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for clients.
Firms with strong balance sheets outperformed firms with weak balance sheets by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the 1994, 1999 and 2004 rate hikes.
Companies with high returns on capital as well as low volatility in their stocks also outperformed their low quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) each.
Debt is becoming a big problem.
Companies with a high proportion of flexible interest will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of the pure equity plays, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see gains from higher yields, although experts differ on how quickly that will take place.
