The Brexit camp (Brexit = Britain's exit from the EU) could gain traction if the economy goes into a slump by 2017
David Cameron's half-baked renegotiation strategy to keep Britain in the EU will run deeper into trouble with each passing day, even without the election of the brilliant Jeremy "Is it Yes or No?" Corbyn to leader of Labour or the TUC, which fell out violently over Europe on Tuesday.
Foreigners have their Corbyns and Nigel Farages too.
A European diplomat friend said the other day that some member states, as deeply mired in various crises as the EU is, and not always through their own fault, are fed up with Britain's home-grown agenda of split concessions and disruptive treaty changes they mostly don't want.
In Brighton, the TUC decided at its annual meeting that it doesn't like them either if they put social protection at risk.
We might as well call it Dave and George's selfie agenda.
Prime Ministers and Finance Ministers climb on summits or bilateral meetings in foreign capitals, take a photo of themselves in front of a famous local monument, with or without local bigwigs, then come home and say they are winning allies for reform.
It is always about me.
My European friend who wants an outward-looking Britain inside the EU tent - "Don't leave us alone with France," says Berlin - and lets slip that more and more short-sighted ministers and officials in some capitals have got to the point where they don't care whether we stay or go.
Germany's cautiously level-headed Chancellor Angela Merkel is an ally, but she has been in power for 10 years and wants to leave office before things look bad for her, as happened with the overly long-suffering likes of Thatcher (11 years), Mitterrand (14) and Kohl (16).
France's François Hollande is looking ahead to his re-election or replacement in 2017.
He is also a fading force.
Poland may soon have a nationalist right-wing government, Spain a left-wing one.
It's hard to imagine they'll be bending over backwards to help the selfie Brits, whose energy would be better spent on preventing Scotland's exit from the UK - something they don't want either, because most have similar separatist tendencies.
So some such ministers may even be planning deliberately unhelpful remarks, very SNP-style, during Britain's 2017 referendum campaign to speed up the Brexit process, my friend suspects.
"The renegotiation was a bust" and "Britain gained nothing of value from the renegotiation."
Europeans know how predatory Fleet Street can be at their expense and what EU sceptics the oligarchy of press barons are, but were not during the Tony Benn-inspired 1975 referendum that supported our entry in 1973 by a ratio of 2:1.
You may faintly remember Boris Johnson, the arch-Euro opportunist who made his name as an "EU straight banana" Brussels correspondent in the early 90s.
For all his craziness, Ed Miliband knew who his enemies were.
This included the medley of tax-fearing scoundrels, phone-hacking foreigners and the pseudo non-nationals who own most of our major newspapers.
Actually, Tony Blair thought similarly of them, but noted that when you're in a cage with a hot gorilla, you're better handing out bananas to distract it rather than becoming its lunch and dinner.
In fact, Miliband was more Blairian than Blair himself when he opposed Cameron's referendum spin, for Blair had put principle above the EU's unadopted constitution, which was then rejected by French and Dutch voters in 2005, opening a back door for him.
The press never forgave him for that either.
But nice Jeremy Corbyn, who gave me a friendly pat on the back in Westminster on Monday - I told him he didn't need to waste any more time on me - seems in danger of repeating Neil Kinnock's boycott Murdoch strategy of the 1980s, a mistake then and now.
It may take time, but he needs to develop a coherent strategy to win over the media, not with me, but certainly with Andrew Marr, whose BBC sofa he left on Sunday.
Corbyn's official position on Europe is - I'll put it kindly - evolving.
He says we should stay in a reformed EU.
Well, most people outside Ukip's traditional blue-dye tendencies and the wilder climes of Tory's small-Englandism can probably all say yes to that.
It's what Hilary "A Benn, but not a Bennite" Benn said on radio and TV this week as the boy scout in him struggled not to admit that Corbyn's appointment of the provocative John McDonnell as shadow chancellor was a bad idea.
It reminded me of the 70's when his old father struggled on TV to be disloyal to his Labour cabinet colleagues without going too far and losing his cabinet job.
Hilary's fight was even more attractive.
But fighting to remain "at all costs" - Benn's phrase - was not what McDonnell said, nor what JC told his fellow MPs and MPs by all accounts at their closed-door meeting on Monday night.
Whatever the maudlin bottom-up image of Corbyn wants to convey - remember he even touched me - message discipline remains important in the age of 24/7 TV and especially in the maelstrom of social media, a hotbed of paranoia and betrayal.
It is right not to give Cameron a free pass on Europe, allowing him to take Labour's support in the referendum campaign for granted, as McDonnell put it.
Simon Jenkins certainly thinks so.
But McDonnell and Corbyn's fundamental ambiguities on EU membership - in line with their Bennite siege economics, their anti-capitalist past - is no longer just a matter of esoteric discussion among left dissidents for whom the narcissism of small difference is a central tenet of dogmatic disputes.
As with his ambiguities on Nato - Tom Watson is rock-solidly convinced that JC is not launching a campaign to leave - foreign diplomats will be obliged to try to make sense of everything for their superiors at home.
Why should Paris or Berlin waste political capital - they also have distrustful voters - to make concessions to the British when it can all be meaningless?
The US is already pretty disappointed with the poor military performance in Iraq, Libya and Syria, even with a Tory government cost-cutting in power, which I was reminded of at Monday's launch by something called the British Influence Security Forum.
Experts criticise Public Health England report on e-cigarettes
Claims by a government-funded agency that e-cigarettes are less harmful than smoking arose from a meeting of 12 people, some with links to the tobacco industry, researchers said.
Experts writing in the British Medical Journal (BMJ) joined Lancet in criticising the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in its report on e-cigarettes.
PHE published the "policy report" last month, describing it as a "comprehensive review of the evidence".
But some researchers have questioned the robustness of the data, pointing to links between some experts and the tobacco industry.
An editorial in the Lancet medical journal last month attacked the "extraordinarily windy basis" on which PHE based its main conclusion.
Writing in BMJ, two other researchers have asked whether the claims are "built on rock or sand".
Martin McKee, Professor of European Public Health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, Professor of Clinical Epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: "A fundamental principle of public health is that strategies should be based on evidence of effectiveness."
They said that the public expects PHE's claim that "the current best estimate is that e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than smoking" to be based on a detailed review of the evidence and modelling.
In fact, this statement comes from a single meeting of 12 people convened to develop a Multi-Criteria Decision Analysis (MCDA) model to synthesise their opinions on the harms of different nicotine-containing products; the results of the meeting were summarised in a research report.
McKee and Capewell said that one sponsor of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose CEO is said to have previously received funding from British American Tobacco (BAT) for an independent study.
He also signed off on BAT's public health credentials in a sustainability report, they said.
One of the 12 participants in the meeting declared receiving funding from an e-cigarette manufacturer, but not the funding he was previously reported to have received from tobacco company Philip Morris International, they added.
The reasons for the selection of the panel's members are not provided, but they include several well-known e-cigarette champions, some of whom also state industry funding in the paper.
Some other participants in this meeting are not known for their expertise in tobacco control.
PHE's tobacco leadership also attended the meeting.
The group's research "tellingly admits" that there is a lack of "hard evidence of harm for most products under most criteria," McKee and Capewell wrote.
However, none of these links or limitations are discussed in the PHE report.
McKee and Capewell said PHE's claims that "there is no evidence to date that e-cigarettes serve as a route to smoking for children or non-smokers" were premature.
Prof Kevin Fenton, director of health and wellbeing at PHE, said BMJ's claims had been responded to before.
He said, "E-cigarettes are significantly less harmful than smoking."
One in two lifelong smokers die from their addiction.
All the evidence suggests that the health risks of e-cigarettes are small in comparison, but that we need to continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about what the evidence does and does not support, especially when there is so much public confusion about the relative dangers compared to tobacco.
Nearly 80,000 people die each year from smoking-related disease, and smoking costs the National Health Service £2 billion a year.
By clearly presenting current evidence that e-cigarettes are not without risk, but represent only a fraction of the harm caused by smoking, we are meeting our national responsibilities.
BBC should abandon EastEnders, says former Channel 4 boss
Former Channel 4 chairman Luke Johnson has said the BBC should stop broadcasting programmes such as EastEnders and The Voice. He said commercial rivals would "give their right arm" to hit shows like Albert Square Soap.
Johnson said the licence fee should only be used to make the kind of programmes that are not broadcast by other UK broadcasters.
