If you want to keep the licence fee, which I don't think is a good idea in the medium or long term, you should at least limit your output to programmes that others don't make or commission.
They broadcast The Voice in a prime time slot because they want to get the widest possible support for its future.
The idea that nobody else would show this is a joke, it's ridiculous, it's nonsense of course.
Johnson said, "I don't see why a regressive tax would fund programmes that could be funded without subsidies.
The Voice is one such programme, EastEnders is another, admittedly both in-house productions.
Frankly, other channels would give their right arm for that.
I struggle to see how this is supposed to be public service television.
I don't think this would reduce the BBC at all.
