Another of the anti-arms trade posters greets commuters on the underground.
The Amnesty video was viewed more than 100,000 times in 24 hours via Facebook and was created by advertising agency VCCP, which works non-profit with the graphic designer and voiceover artist, who also works for free.
VCCP creative director Matt Lever was amazed at the silence around the arms fair ad - through a blank space on the ExCeL calendar - and thought, "Let's give them the campaign they're trying to avoid."
They toyed with inventing a more realistic dodgy corporate ad, but "by blowing it in with bright colours and animation, it sticks more."
"They've done a fantastic job in helping us raise awareness about the sale of illegal torture devices at the fair," says Tom Davies of Amnesty.
'What we need now is for the British government to intervene and guarantee that torture devices are not traded illegally on our doorstep.
Perhaps the most creative art around the arms fair comes from the area within ExCeL where exhibitors flog fantastically euphemistic products.
