This includes a "uniquely shaped warhead that delivers outstanding after-effects inside the target."
Whatever that does, it won't be pleasant.
Eight golden rules for dorm life
Eleven years ago I moved into a dorm as an oblivious 19-year-old, still believing in berets and moral relativism, but only now remembering the strained smiles of those I annoyed - and the numerous, long-winded complaints about others.
Most of what I learned can be distilled into eight simple rules.
Moving into student accommodation ranges from mildly nerve-wracking to absolutely terrifying.
It's tempting to gossip: People telling you where you're from, if and where you took sabbatical, where you stand on Corbyn and why you "honestly neither love nor hate Marmite because seriously guys, it's just a yeast extract HAHAHA, I'm in my room."
Take a breath.
And help others do the same - Ask questions and show interest.
It steers the conversation and helps you pick out the people you like as opposed to those you wouldn't talk to even if your eyelashes caught fire and they were fire extinguishers.
Let people.
People's rooms often turn into drinks receptions, movie-night venues and communal meeting places, but they're also where people get dressed and adjust their underwear.
Related to this: Don't think about starting a relationship at uni
Introverts get rough treatment at university.
Your room should be a refuge, but many halls of residence form a room-to-room strolling culture that is friendly and social and can lead to lifelong friendships.
This can be hell for someone trying to recover.
Nothing in the culture allows you to say, "I like you, and I want our friendship to continue, but you need to leave so I can get back the energy I spent interacting with you."
Try to sense when a fellow student is exhausted from socialising - and text them instead of knocking.
Speaking of knocking, do it.
One guy in my dorms had the idea that an unlocked door was an invitation.
He saw a few things.
Make friends by baking.
As you start uni at the height of baking mania, knocking on people's doors to introduce yourself with a plate of brownies is less weird than the 1950s greeting "Welcome to the neighbourhood, I baked you something". So, now please smile as I ask you a few personal questions."
Offering homemade treats is a great way to make friends.
Your housemates will feel obliged to chat and may end up associating your face with a tasty surprise.
Of course, this depends on whether you are a decent baker.
Poorly mixed lumps of flour, sugar and fat will cause people to feign sleep when you knock.
Stealing food is a common crime in dormitories.
Of course stealing chicken is stealing, but so is taking a drop of milk for your tea?
Check with the milk owner.
Chances are they'll say help yourself even if they're cooking inside.
If someone steals your stuff, that's annoying, and you have my sympathy - but try to deal with it in a more balanced way than my flatmate, who added washing-up liquid to her milk to punish thieves.
She is now in prison.
You shouldn't make noise that stops people from sleeping or working.
It's not just about being a decent human being, but that you are literally one of those people who are in a glass house.
A girl in my hallway asked her neighbours if they minded turning down the drum & bass a bit because it was three in the morning and she had an exam that morning.
They responded by playing the music even louder.
When they finally stopped at 5 o'clock, she kindly let her neighbours sleep for another two hours before she let her own music blare, locked her door and left for her three-hour exam.
Wouldn't it be romantic if your future spouse happened to move into the same student dorm?
Conversely, wouldn't it be abysmally embarrassing if you mistook a flatmate for your future spouse, made a pass at her, broke up again and then had to see her every day and perhaps witness her dragging all their mutual friends over to her?
Of course, the heart goes its own way - but if a hot roommate is definitely not your future spouse, at least try to talk some sense into your abdomen.
In that exciting moment when you realise someone has left their keys in their unlocked room, the line between a prank and bullying is finer than it seems.
A good prank is funny, but it only takes moments for it to boomerang.
Teach a valuable and amusing lesson about safety by hiding - but never mess up someone's room with toothpaste and shampoo.
Lock their door and put their keys in a glass of water, which you then put in the freezer - but don't staple their possessions to the ceiling more than twice.
