At their most anticipated meeting of the year, Federal Reserve strategists will spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras mahogany table deciding whether it is time to raise the federal funds rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Looming over them at one end of the ornate, two-storey meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the nation's economic interests before all else.
The central bank has a dual mandate from Congress: maximise US employment and keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, Fed leaders have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And that third mandate could be the X factor in a decision too close to predict. It will be known on Thursday whether the US economy is ready to be weaned from the unprecedented stimulus of near-zero short-term interest rates since late 2008.
Although most data show the economy growing solidly, recent turmoil in global financial markets could make already cautious Fed officials anxious about adding to that volatility by raising the federal funds rate - even by a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labour market and inflation are going to be the primary things they're watching," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise rates, the heightened uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to continue to wait," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is unsettling the financial market.
About half of economists surveyed recently by Bloomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator showing only a 30% chance of a hike.
This suggests a fall in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate, unless strategists soften the blow by promising that another hike is a long way off.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4 per cent, to 16,599.85.
The action was triggered by expectations that Fed policy will keep rates on hold this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed lifted rates at this point," he said.
If it does, "it would have to go very far in its statement to reassure financial markets not to panic."
Other experts argued that a rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage point this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that she expected to raise the rate this year despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress was needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labour market this year has been solid.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and near the level the Fed considers full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation has been running steadily below the central bank's 2% annual target, Fed officials said the main reason was the temporary effect of sharply lower oil prices.
The economy "can handle higher interest rates and needs them because of the tightness in the labour market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world winced late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell more than 16% below its peak in May as investors worried that a slowdown in China's economy would curb global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now down nearly 10% from its May high.
For Fed officials, the market turmoil affects the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
"If it weren't for the events in the financial markets and the news about the weakness in the Chinese economy over the last couple of weeks, they would be tightening the reins this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now he predicts it will wait at least a month to get a better handle on the impact.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the US economy, and there is almost no reliable data describing developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed's main concerns, so technically it should not be included in its decision-making.
But the bottom line is that the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The central bank's influence has been enormous in recent years.
The mere suggestion by then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could "tighten" its monetary expansion sparked confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials can be expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of global wealth management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA. noted this month that "the Fed has a history of overreacting to financial market moves with seemingly no link to economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, which advocates for a rate hike, cited decisions in 1998-99 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut its key interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three meetings "despite limited discernible effects on growth in the US", Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed those cuts.
The Fed should only put aspects of financial stability first during a severe crisis like the 2008 market collapse, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's rate-setting committee.
The recent turmoil doesn't come close to that level, he said.
"It certainly doesn't want to get into the situation where it's afraid to raise interest rates because markets are upset," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
'The Federal Reserve Act still contains the dual mandate and doesn't mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I don't think she should get ahead of the curve.
