Weight loss surgery can be helpful for mildly overweight diabetics.
The benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly overweight people with type 2 diabetes may last at least five years, according to a new study.
It is too early to say whether slightly overweight people with diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatments.
"The mortality data take a long time to show anything," said Dr Robin Blackstone, a weight-loss surgery expert who wrote an editorial on the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight-loss surgeries, or bariatric surgery, use different methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been done on people who are morbidly obese with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a certain amount of weight in relation to height, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or more indicates that someone is overweight, and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers from Taiwan's Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected in a study since 2007 comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastric sleeve formation - to medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly overweight.
The average BMI among those who underwent this surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in this study.
Meanwhile, among those who received non-surgical diabetes treatments, BMI remained about the same at 29.
Among those who underwent surgical intervention, diabetes resolved completely in 36% and partially in 28%.
In the medically-treated group, by comparison, diabetes resolved completely in only one per cent and partially in only about two per cent.
In addition, results for controls of blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol were "generally better in the 'surgical' group," the authors found.
The researchers also monitored patient blood levels of haemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
Haemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 per cent, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average haemoglobin A1c level dropped from around 9 per cent to around 6 per cent.
In the medical therapy group, however, it remained stable at around 8 per cent.
But this better "glycaemic control" - as reflected in the improved haemoglobin A1c level - did not reduce mortality over five years, according to lead researcher Dr Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared average outcomes for the two types of surgery.
By the fifth year, compared to the gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group had lost more weight (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg), achieved greater declines in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%), and were more likely to have completely overcome diabetes (46.9% vs. 16.7%).
While the new study shows no survival benefit of surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of heavier people in Sweden that surgery leads to longer life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona, College of Medicine Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29 per cent less likely to die over 15 years - compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study showed no survival benefit among surgery patients, Blackstone said it was reassuring for people with a BMI below 35 who were interested in the procedure.
"That's the critical point of this study because it says this surgery is lower in this lower BMI group" with no increased risk of death or kidney disease, she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously once the patient's BMI is between 27 and 30.
"I think we wait too long to get people to take this seriously," she said.
I think that once they have accumulated these genetic changes that have firmly linked their bodies to obesity and diabetes, reversal is really hard."
