Poison control centres in the US are reporting a nearly 400 per cent increase in the number of children under the age of 12 swallowing strong alcohol hand sanitizers, according to the Georgia Poison Center.
According to Dr Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Center, cases of hand sanitizer ingestion among children under 12 reporting poison control centres increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children are increasingly getting these products, and unfortunately a percentage of them end up going to the emergency room," Lopez told CNN.
He said some children drink disinfectant on purpose, while some do it to impress their friends or for a dare on social media.
Videos on YouTube show teens drinking disinfectant just for a cheap experience.
Teenagers have allegedly mixed disinfectant with alcoholic mouthwash to get a harder drink.
Younger children may be lured by attractive scents of disinfectants.
"A child doesn't think this is bad for them," Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand sanitisers) are those that are scented.
There are sanitisers with strawberry, grape and orange scents that are very appealing to children.
Hand sanitisers contain somewhere between 45 and 95 per cent alcohol.
Especially for young children, just a few squirts can lead to alcohol poisoning.
"It's highly concentrated alcohol," Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the Poison Control Centre at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 station in Kansa City.
So, you wouldn't leave a sip of whiskey around, but people leave these hand sanitizers within reach of children, and when children get to it, it's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently ingested four squirts of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school, was taken to an emergency room for treatment.
Her blood alcohol concentration was 179, twice the threshold that is legally considered drunk for an adult, said Dr Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah slurred her words and was unable to walk when she arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight at a separate children's hospital for signs of brain trauma because the girl had fallen through alcohol and hit her head, Ritchey said.
"It was very scary," Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal for my child.
Lopez has advised parents and teachers to use alcohol-free products or disinfectant wipes and to store hand sanitizer out of the child's reach.
Beyond alcohol poisoning, some sanitizers have been linked to deaths.
