Melbourne Storm coach Craig Bellamy hits back at rival over wrestling allegations
Melbourne Storm coach Craig Bellamy has described criticism of his players' tackling as "agenda-setting" by two NRL Premier League favourites.
Sydney Roosters coach Trent Robinson said referees allowed Storm players to "wrestle" with his team during the Storm's high-scoring win in the qualifying final in Sydney on Friday night.
Brisbane Broncos coach Wayne Bennett made a barely veiled comment about the Storm team after his side's final win over North Queensland Cowboys on Saturday night. He called the game a "showcase" of rugby league and said the Queensland two were not "too good" at wrestling.
Bellamy defended his team's tacklimg and said they were only focused on their "contact" when tackling.
Bellamy added that criticism of his team from two leading coaches gave him confidence as it meant they were worried about being beaten by the Storm team.
"That keeps coming up - I didn't hear Trent Robinson talking about wrestling when they beat us 24-2," Bellamy said on Wednesday.
I can guarantee we haven't changed anything in our defensive system or techniques all year. But in the last six weeks we've made our contact at tackles a real focus, and that's turned it around for us.
Trent has been there for three years now, and he obviously has a great team to coach. So he's probably not used to losing, so it was a bit of a shock for him.
It's funny how this keeps coming up at this time of year.
