Serbian man bailed $200,000 after drug charge
A man facing a possible life sentence for his attempt to gain possession of 40 kilograms of cocaine smuggled into Queensland has been released on $200,000 bail.
Marko Maksimovic, 29, was one of five men arrested last month after federal police found 100kg of the drug on the yacht Solay, which came from South America via Vanuatu and docked in Coomera in August.
Maksimovic was observed meeting his co-accused at the marina during the morning and later at the Coomera Roadhouse café, where police found 40 kilogrammes of the drug in a Toyota Echo.
Despite a possible life sentence for attempting to possess a commercial quantity of cocaine, Maksimovic's lawyer argued that there was no evidence that he attempted to possess the entire quantity and that could have been at the café for an innocent reason.
Supreme Court Justice Peter Flanagan was concerned about Maksimovic's flight risk.
He has clear ties to Serbia.
He often travels to Serbia," he told the court on Wednesday.
In the criminal case, he had lied to the police about his whereabouts.
Maksimovic's mother and stepfather had jointly offered $200,000 bail as security to secure his release.
"After reading the affidavits of the two individuals, it is clear that the requirement of $200,000 security is a real financial burden," Justice Flanagan said.
But that alone will not be enough to stop him from failing to appear, he warned.
Maksimovic was released on bail on conditions that he surrender his Australian and Serbian passports, report to police daily and abide by a 18:00-06:00 curfew.
Stevan Hogg used girl's phone to lure paedophile into sending pictures
A paedophile used the phone of an 11-year-old girl to request child abuse images.
Stevan Hogg took the girl's phone when she was asleep, logged into an online messaging service from which he received a series of indecent images of children sent to him by another user.
The girl later woke up to discover the phone missing and found it in the sleeping Hogg's hand.
She looked through it, found the confusing messages and immediately alerted her mother.
Police dealt with it and saw the five pictures, then analysed computers found at the address and discovered "concerning" web searches that used terms to search for indecent images of children.
Hogg then claimed to officers that he did it because it would lead to "paedophiles on the internet" and he then "pretended to be a police officer to scare them".
Prosecutor Eilidh Robertson told Dundee Sheriff Court "he said it was an addiction - that he was addicted to scaring people".
He admitted the searches on the computer were carried out by him, but said it was done because he wanted to claim to be a police officer to scare paedophiles.
He was asked about his conversations with the unknown person who sent him the pictures and whom he asked to send more photos.
He said he did it to lure them.
He said he was sick in the head when he drank and said he then wanted to see pictures of rape and murder.
Ms Robertson added: "When the girl found the messages on the phone she called her mother and was shaking and crying.
