Hewlett-Packard to cut up to 30,000 jobs
Hewlett-Packard is expected to cut 25,000 to 30,000 jobs as part of restructuring and cost-cutting efforts in the company's services.
HP will split into two publicly traded companies later this year, separating its computer and printer business from its faster-growing enterprise hardware and services businesses.
The expected job cuts will result in a charge of more than $2.7 billion starting in the fourth quarter, HP said in a statement.
"These restructuring actions will enable a more competitive, sustainable cost structure for the new Hewlett Packard Enterprise," said Meg Whitman, HP chairman and chief executive, who is expected to lead the unit after the separation.
"Hewlett Packard Enterprise will be smaller and more focused than HP is today, and we have a broad and deeper portfolio of businesses to help companies transition to a new style of doing business," Whitman said.
'As a standalone company, we are better positioned than ever to meet the changing needs of our customers around the world.
Hewlett Packard Enterprise has more than $50 billion in annual revenue and "will be focused on delivering unprecedented, integrated technology solutions to businesses," according to a company statement.
It splits up a company founded in the 1930s by Stanford University graduates Bill Hewlett and Dave Packard to make electrical equipment and whose Palo Alto garage has been called "the birthplace of Silicon Valley".
HP has undergone a massive restructuring to cope with the move away from traditional PCs to mobile devices.
The move by HP, the world's second-largest PC maker and one of the largest US tech companies, is the latest in the sector, based on the belief that narrowly focused companies perform better.
