FriendsFest: the comedy show that teaches us serious lessons about male friendships.
The lack of similar portrayals in shows is obvious, especially in light of how the need for men to open up has now become more desperate than ever, as evidenced by suicide rates among young men at a 15-year high.
In 2013, it was the leading cause of death among men aged 20 to 45 in the UK, and it remains three times more common among men than women.
In an effort to tackle the problem, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) announced 2015 as the Year of the Man, aiming to challenge the culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of the fight to overcome this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students with depressive symptoms found that if the sufferer had a high enough percentage of friends with "healthy moods," their chances of recovery doubled.
For those who are not depressed, a circle of mentally healthy friends halves the risks of mental problems.
But of course, you have to have friends first for a friendship to work.
In the age of communication conducted via social media, with its emphasis on style over substance, the immediacy of the response is often more important than meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to appear strong, fun-loving and successful, even when in reality isolation dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the expense of intrinsic values - our inner longing for personal development and friendship, which has a much deeper impact on our mental health.
And as a video game inventor and billionaire recently explained, money really can't buy happiness.
The beauty of Friends was that this focus was turned on its head.
Each character was defined not by their work, but by their personality, which shone through their interactions as friends.
The humour of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, moments watching football in comfy armchairs, and Ross's longing for Rachel all came from the knowledge that men can definitely relate to this, even if they often hold back from fully exploring their feelings.
As one telephone counselling worker explained it to me.... "my listening role to people who are feeling depressed and suicidal has really shown me clearly how even the smallest interactions from friends can make a difference."
The men who contact us often feel unable to talk to friends.
The old phrase 'I can handle it' has a huge impact, like feeling like it's perceived as weakness to talk openly about problems."
Friends is one of the shows that comes to mind when I try to offer more long-term coping mechanisms.
It clearly presents the small moments of male friendships.
As much as my objective outsider status over the phone may help people in moments of despair, the long-term support comes from a personal network of family and friends.
And so, if you're attending Comedy Central FriendsFest this weekend with the set completely revamped to celebrate, why not take your friends for a drink at Central Perk.
Or, better yet, if you see someone sitting around alone in Starbucks, give them a smile and say hello.
You never know what difference your friendship could make.
Friends airs on Comedy Central from start to finish - the entire 236 episodes - for #FriendsFest
Di Maria scores to help PSG crush Malmo
Angel Di Maria celebrates with Blaise Matuidi and Edinson Cavani after scoring against Malmo.
Di Maria scores on his Champions League debut on Tuesday to help PSG move past Malmo.
Here's the match report and reaction.
Angel Di Maria and Edinson Cavani stayed the course as Paris Saint-Germain kicked off their Champions League season with an extremely comfortable 2-0 win over Malmo at Prinzenparkstadion on Tuesday.
Di Maria scored less than four minutes into his Champions League debut as PSG set the French champions on their way, but they missed a series of opportunities after that before finally increasing their lead when Cavani scored a 61st-minute header.
With Real Madrid and Shakhtyor Donetsk also in Group A, Paris need a strong start against the Swedish champions as they seek not only qualification for the knockout rounds but improvement en route to the quarter-finals in each of their last three campaigns.
But while they got the points, it was not a class game from Laurent Blanc's side with Zlatan Ibrahimovic's missed chances in front of goal. He was later substituted in the match against his hometown team and against the club with which he started his illustrious career back in 1999.
"It is not easy to win at home or away in the Champions League. So it's a good start to win 2-0, cause problems for our opponents and look back relaxed, even if there are certain things we need to perfect as the season goes on," Blanc said.
"It's a good omen.
We wanted to win and we won, although I regret that we didn't score one or two more goals."
Ibrahimovic returned from injury in one of three changes to the Paris team that held on for a 2-2 draw at home to Bordeaux in the First Division at the weekend, but he was cut out by Di Maria in the fourth minute.
The Argentine winger was tipped as the man to take PSG to the next level in Europe when he was acquired from Manchester United last month and he hinted at why when he ran on to Marco Verratti's pass behind the Malmo defence before finishing beautifully past Johan Wiland into the far corner of the net.
However, if anyone thought PSG were going to pull off a big win, they were disappointed.
Malmo, who beat Celtic in a play-off to reach this stage, entered kick-off with nine internationals on the pitch and, with a five-man defence and two lined up deep in midfield, were tough opponents.
But apart from a Nikola Djurdjic shot that went wide of Kevin Trapp's post in the 34th minute, they offered little in attack.
Instead, PSG gave themselves away at times, with some misplaced passes and poor finishing, not least from Ibrahimovic, who fluffed no fewer than five attempts in the first half alone and was then abandoned after Cavani put him in after the restart.
Still, he showed much more skill in bringing his teammates into play, and it was a pass from Ibrahimovic that Di Maria turned into a spinning shot that was deflected past the post by Wiland in the 52nd minute ...
The second goal finally came just after the hour mark thanks to Cavani. It was the Uruguayan's sixth goal of the season after Ibrahimovic had latched onto a left-wing cross from Maxwell.
That ended any thoughts of Malmö getting back into the game and only an excellent intervention from Wiland at point-blank range to stop David Luiz kept the final score down before substitute Ezequiel Lavezzi was denied a goal at the end.
Malmo coach Age Hareide later admitted PSG were playing a class above his team and the Norwegian said: "Our last Champions League game was in December last year.
Since then we have only played in the Swedish League, which is not the same level.
The qualifying games are not enough."
Hats off to Paris!
It was a great game from them!
Glencore raises $2.5 billion through share sales
Switzerland-based mining giant Glencore, hit by collapsing commodity prices, raised $2.5 billion on Wednesday through a share sale as part of its huge debt repayment plan.
London-registered Glencore said in a statement it sold about £1.6 billion worth of new shares to pay off its own debt.
The company, which has lost 57 per cent of its market value this year, is struggling with falling commodity prices as China's economic downturn squeezes demand and has a devastating effect on markets.
The rights issue sent Glencore's share price soaring to the top of the London Stock Exchange in early Wednesday morning trading.
The shares jumped 2.77 per cent to 131.60p on the FTSE 100 index, which opened 0.69 per cent higher.
Glencore had announced the $2.5 billion share sale last week as part of broader plans to pay down about a third of its $30 billion debt.
The company sold the new holdings at 125 pence a share, a 2.4 per cent discount to Tuesday's closing price.
It gave up 1.3 billion shares worth up to 9.99 per cent of the group.
Concerns about long-term inhibited growth in China have cut iron ore prices by about half, with coal, copper and other commodity prices down 20 to 40 per cent.
White House confirms Xi Jinping's visit to Washington
Chinese President Xi Jinping will make a state visit to the US at the end of the month, the White House confirmed in a statement on Tuesday.
The visit, Xi's first official one to Washington, will take place on 25 September and reciprocates President Barack Obama's trip to Beijing last November, the statement said.
The US president and first lady Michelle Obama will also host Xi and his wife Peng Liyuan at a state dinner that evening after the two leaders held bilateral talks.
"President Xi's visit will provide an opportunity to expand U.S.-China cooperation on a range of global, regional, and bilateral issues of mutual interest, while also allowing President Obama and President Xi to constructively address areas of disagreement," the statement added.
XI, whose visit was initially announced in February, is expected to meet several US technology leaders in Seattle on his way to Washington before continuing to New York City for the UN General Assembly in September.
Obama and Xi are expected to address a range of contentious issues, including Washington's concerns about alleged cyber espionage by China and its growing assertiveness in the disputed waters of the South China Sea.
