Xi urges economy to open wider to world
The economy must open wider to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with steering reform on Tuesday.
"China should work to attract foreign investment and know-how and improve business start-up strategies," he said in an address to the 16th meeting of the Central Leading Group for Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
Encouraging start-ups and pushing forward reforms will bring about new momentum and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The leadership group has adopted a series of policies, including a negative list to regulate market access, relax border control policies, encourage state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to raise private capital, and overhaul the resident reporting system.
According to the statement, a negative list will be drawn up to identify sectors and enterprises that are not eligible for investment.
The system will be gradually tested and improved through test programmes.
The initiative is significant as it gives the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensures a business environment based on the rule of law and makes the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls on the powers delegated to companies and ensure that companies decide how they conduct their business.
The statement also said China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
More areas will be opened to private investment as part of a bid to open up state-controlled sectors.
"The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of leveraged enterprises and provide better services to them," the statement said.
It will also make it easier for foreigners to apply for permanent residency or the "green card" by streamlining requirements and making the application process easier.
Guaranteeing the right of lawyers to practice and appointing professional judges and prosecutors were also discussed at a meeting.
Premier Li Keqiang and key leaders such as Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting, according to a statement released after the meeting.
